  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety and self-doubt that individuals experience when they fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. As a retired immigrant from a place where STEM fields were less accessible, I've seen firsthand how this can stifle potential. For instance, during my time as a mechanic and later as a hobbyist in engineering, I noticed that many young people from my background would hesitate to pursue technical paths because they believed they weren't 'smart enough' in math or science. This isn't just about individual confidence; it's a systemic issue that affects the diversity of ideas in our fields. Addressing it is crucial, but it must be done thoughtfully. We should focus on early education programs that build confidence through hands-on projects rather than rote memorization. In my community, we've found that storytelling—sharing real-life examples of people who overcame similar doubts—helps young minds see themselves in those paths. Also, creating inclusive environments where everyone feels valued, regardless of their background, is key. I've observed that when students feel safe to ask questions without fear of judgment, their performance improves significantly. The challenge is to implement these changes without overwhelming the system. It's a slow process, but one worth the effort. After all, STEM should be a place where everyone can thrive, not just those who fit a narrow mold.",
